I wil probably catch some static for this but here goes....
Lemon oil is crap!!!
All it is, is a mineral oil with a scent, it has NO magical qualities
becuse of the lemon, but mineral oil does have a slight cleaning effect (
it is good for cleaning your hands). The Antique Wizard is right that it
is important to remove ALL traces of the oil. The biggest problem is that
people truly believe that oil, be it lemon, linseed or whatever, has some
ability to &quot;feed&quot; finishes and &quot;feed&quot; wood. It does not. It is chemically
impossible.
It is important to remember that when cleaning the surface of a piece of
furniture, tou are not cleaning wood, you are cleaning that very thin
surface coating (finish) be it shellac, nitrocellulose, urushi, or even
(yuk) polyurethane.
A better understanding of what you are cleaning is important before any
recommendations can be given.
However, I can say that aqueous solutions (water based) are just as
important as solvent based ones. There many different types of dirt and
grime, some that only water and a soap can move, some that only solvents
can move.
Many people tout &quot;Murphy's Oil Soap&quot; which is fine, but it, too, has no
magical effects. It also has some alcohol in it, so be careful with some
finished (shellac etc).
The simplest way to clean furniture coatings is a low odor minerals
spirits, followed by a MILD soap(not detergent) and water solution (&lt;5%),
then a high quality paste wax(my favorite is &quot;Beatue&quot;).
This very basic and I strongly advise caution, If you have a very old and
valuable antique, consult a professional about that particular piece.

