"/> Yeah, you've got to be careful with any cleaning/waxing/polishing product
... some contain alcohol, which may cause problems with shellac-based
finishes, some may contain abrasives ( particularely some metal-cleaners
that one might try on furniture hardware, for example) that can dull or
damage the finish, while still others may contain other solvents that can
effect a variety of finishes. Butcher's wax is really great stuff, but it
contains turpentine, which does a super job cleaning and removing old built
up grease and grim and wax, but, as you note, can also soften and damage
certain other finishes. Many &quot;good&quot; waxes contain some kind of solvent,
since in their natural form natural waxes are a tough, durable solid mass.
The solvent dissolves the wax so you can spread it in a thin layer and when
the solvent evaporates, the wax reverts back to the hard durable material
again, but in a thin protective film over the surface. You really have to
know what finish is on the piece, then know what solvents are in the
product and be sure that the two are compatible. MOST commercial products
have a cautionary statement that advises of finishes known to be
incompatible (like Butcher's wax and asphalt tile) and advise that you try
it in an inconspicuous place first ... Good advice.

